<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n04149o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n04" href="#n04149o">N04 (VI.B.25)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n04all.htm#n04149o"> 149(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> clothyard arrows</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Bow and <mark>Arrow</mark> in History / And its Place in Sport]</font> The long-bow was five feet, and its shaft a <mark>clothyard</mark>; and this weapon in the hands of a Welshman penetrated an oak door four inches thick, and stood out a handbreadth on the other side, at Abergavenny in 1182. <small> <a name="II4aug23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#II4aug23"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (4 August 1923) 5/3</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Clothyard. The yard by which cloth was measured: chiefly in &lsquo;cloth-yard shaft&rsquo;, applied in ballads to an arrow of the long bow. This is now the statute yard of 36 inches (OED).</mm> </dd></dl>
